{"parentUuid":"8b9db839-bae8-47d5-801f-4fd5bd0427f7","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"4d655e02-383b-40f2-b85f-7eec712c1627","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01ULYRaYQyQ5X2A2KVDc3TB5","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# First-Time Contributors\n2\t\n3\tWelcome. This guide is for people who are new to Entire, new to open source, or\n4\tjust want a careful path through their first contribution to this repository.\n5\t\n6\tThe main contribution rules live in [CONTRIBUTING.md](../CONTRIBUTING.md). Treat\n7\tthat file as the source of truth. This page slows the process down and explains\n8\twhere to start, what to say, what to run, and what to expect after you open a\n9\tpull request.\n10\t\n11\t## Who This Is For\n12\t\n13\tStart here if any of these are true:\n14\t\n15\t- You have never opened a pull request before.\n16\t- You have contributed to other projects, but not to Entire.\n17\t- You want help finding a contribution that is small enough to finish.\n18\t- You are unsure how to ask maintainers for the right amount of context.\n19\t\n20\tIf you are already comfortable with this repo, use the shorter workflow in\n21\t[CONTRIBUTING.md](../CONTRIBUTING.md).\n22\t\n23\t## Choose a First Contribution\n24\t\n25\tStart by browsing [GitHub Issues](https://github.com/entireio/cli/issues) for\n26\tissues that describe behavior you can reproduce, mention a command or workflow\n27\tyou can try locally, or feel concrete enough that you can explain the problem\n28\tback in your own words. You can also check the `#looking-for-contributors`\n29\tchannel in Discord. You do not need to understand the whole project before\n30\tasking about an issue.\n31\t\n32\tGood first contributions are small, clear, and easy to review. For this repo,\n33\tthat usually means one of these:\n34\t\n35\t- Reproducing a bug you personally hit and adding the missing test.\n36\t- Clarifying a confusing CLI message, help text, or setup step.\n37\t- Adding a focused test around existing command behavior.\n38\t- Fixing a small platform-specific issue on macOS, Linux, or Windows.\n39\t- Improving README or contributor instructions after you hit real friction.\n40\t\n41\tWhen looking at an issue, favor ones where you can explain the problem back in\n42\tyour own words. It is okay if you do not know the fix yet. If an issue is broad,\n43\tcomment with the part you think you can tackle and ask whether that slice would\n44\tbe useful.\n45\t\n46\tIf you do not already have a specific problem in mind, ask in\n47\t`#looking-for-contributors` and mention what you are comfortable with, such as\n48\tGo tests, CLI output, setup issues, Windows behavior, or README/contributor\n49\twording. A maintainer can usually point you toward a safer slice than browsing\n50\talone can.\n51\t\n52\tAs a first PR, avoid broad architecture changes, new agent integrations, command\n53\trenames, checkpoint strategy changes, or anything that changes git history\n54\tbehavior unless a maintainer has already helped define the scope.\n55\t\n56\t## Comment Before You Start\n57\t\n58\tBefore starting non-trivial code work, leave a short comment on the issue or\n59\tstart a new issue. This helps avoid duplicated effort and gives maintainers a\n60\tchance to redirect you before you spend time on the wrong approach.\n61\t\n62\tA good first comment is specific:\n63\t\n64\t```text\n65\tHi, I am new to Entire and would like to work on this.\n66\t\n67\tI was able to reproduce the issue by running:\n68\t\n69\t  entire status\n70\t\n71\tMy plan is to update the error message in <file or command area> and add a\n72\tfocused test for the behavior. Does that sound like the right direction?\n73\t```\n74\t\n75\tIf you are not starting from an existing issue, open one with the smallest\n76\tconcrete problem you can describe:\n77\t\n78\t```text\n79\tI hit confusing behavior while running `entire enable` on macOS.\n80\t\n81\tExpected: the command would explain which agent config was missing.\n82\tActual: the command exited with \"not configured\".\n83\t\n84\tI can reproduce this locally. Would a small PR that improves the message and\n85\tadds a focused test be useful?\n86\t```\n87\t\n88\tYou do not need a perfect plan. Showing what you have tried and where you are\n89\theaded is usually enough.\n90\t\n91\t## Set Up the Repository\n92\t\n93\tFork the repository on GitHub, then clone your fork:\n94\t\n95\t```bash\n96\tgit clone git@github.com:YOUR-USERNAME/cli.git\n97\tcd cli\n98\t```\n99\t\n100\tAdd the upstream repository so you can pull in maintainer changes later:\n101\t\n102\t```bash\n103\tgit remote add upstream git@github.com:entireio/cli.git\n104\tgit fetch upstream\n105\t```\n106\t\n107\tInstall the local toolchain:\n108\t\n109\t```bash\n110\tmise trust\n111\tmise install\n112\tgo mod download\n113\tmise run build\n114\t```\n115\t\n116\tVerify the setup with the normal test suite:\n117\t\n118\t```bash\n119\tmise run test\n120\t```\n121\t\n122\tIf setup fails, include the command you ran, the full error text, your OS, and\n123\tthe output of `go version` when asking for help.\n124\t\n125\t## Create a Branch\n126\t\n127\tCreate a branch from the latest `main`:\n128\t\n129\t```bash\n130\tgit switch main\n131\tgit pull upstream main\n132\tgit switch -c fix/clearer-enable-error\n133\t```\n134\t\n135\tUse a branch name that describes the change. Examples:\n136\t\n137\t- `fix/clearer-enable-error`\n138\t- `test/session-status-output`\n139\t- `docs/setup-troubleshooting-note`\n140\t\n141\t## Make a Small Change\n142\t\n143\tKeep your first pull request narrow. A focused PR is easier to review and easier\n144\tto finish.\n145\t\n146\tGood first PR shapes:\n147\t\n148\t- One failing behavior plus its test.\n149\t- One small error message improvement.\n150\t- One test-only clarification.\n151\t- One README or setup clarification based on a real problem you hit.\n152\t\n153\tAvoid bundling unrelated cleanup with your first PR. If you notice extra things\n154\twhile working, leave yourself a note and open a follow-up issue or PR later.\n155\t\n156\t## Use AI Carefully\n157\t\n158\tEntire CLI is not an agent. It is a CLI for capturing and navigating AI-agent\n159\twork, so it is completely normal to use coding agents while contributing.\n160\tThere is no need to tell us that you used AI in your work.\n161\t\n162\tUse whatever agent and workflow you like. We hope you like Goose, of course. The\n163\timportant rule is that you are responsible for the final code, tests, and docs.\n164\tBefore submitting a PR, review the diff yourself. PRs that look generated,\n165\tunreviewed, or \"vibe coded\" without a human pass may be closed.\n166\t\n167\tQuick responsible AI tips:\n168\t\n169\t- **Think first.** Agents tend to jump straight to code. Ask the agent to explore\n170\t  the codebase first, explain the relevant architecture, and propose an approach\n171\t  before it edits files.\n172\t- **Push back on shortcuts.** Watch for trivial tests, overly wide types,\n173\t  optional fields added just to satisfy the compiler, swallowed errors, and\n174\t  copied local patterns that do not actually fit.\n175\t- **Notice uncertainty.** If the agent keeps declaring that it understands the\n176\t  issue but the patches are not converging, stop and reframe the task. Use what\n177\t  you learned to start a smaller attempt.\n178\t- **Cut the bloat.** Remove redundant comments, just-in-case logging,\n179\t  over-defensive branches, and tests that only check implementation details\n180\t  instead of user-visible behavior.\n181\t\n182\t## Run the Right Checks\n183\t\n184\tFor wording-only changes, run a lightweight sanity check:\n185\t\n186\t```bash\n187\tgit diff --check\n188\t```\n189\t\n190\tFor Go code changes, run:\n191\t\n192\t```bash\n193\tmise run fmt\n194\tmise run lint\n195\tmise run test\n196\t```\n197\t\n198\tBefore a larger PR or when a maintainer asks for full verification, run:\n199\t\n200\t```bash\n201\tmise run check\n202\t```\n203\t\n204\tDo not run real agent E2E tests unless a maintainer explicitly asks you to. They\n205\tcan make real agent API calls. The deterministic canary E2E suite is safe to run\n206\twhen your change touches E2E prompt wording or test infrastructure:\n207\t\n208\t```bash\n209\tmise run test:e2e:canary\n210\t```\n211\t\n212\t## Commit Your Work\n213\t\n214\tCommit with a short, descriptive message:\n215\t\n216\t```bash\n217\tgit add <files you changed>\n218\tgit commit -m \"Clarify enable error when agent config is missing\"\n219\t```\n220\t\n221\tEntire is used to dogfood Entire. If you have the Entire CLI installed and\n222\tenabled in this repository, the git hook may add an `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer\n223\tto your commit message automatically. That is expected. See\n224\t[Using Entire While Contributing](../CONTRIBUTING.md#using-entire-while-contributing)\n225\tfor the full details.\n226\t\n227\t## Open a Pull Request\n228\t\n229\tPush your branch to your fork:\n230\t\n231\t```bash\n232\tgit push -u origin fix/clearer-enable-error\n233\t```\n234\t\n235\tThen open a pull request against `entireio/cli` on GitHub.\n236\t\n237\tIn the PR description, include:\n238\t\n239\t- The issue it addresses, if there is one.\n240\t- A short summary of what changed.\n241\t- The checks you ran, such as `mise run test` or `git diff --check`.\n242\t- Anything you want reviewers to pay special attention to.\n243\t\n244\tIf your PR is not ready for final review yet, open it as a draft. Draft PRs are\n245\tuseful when you want early feedback on direction.\n246\t\n247\t## Respond to Review\n248\t\n249\tReview is part of the contribution, not a sign that you did something wrong.\n250\tEntire PRs may receive automated Copilot comments and maintainer comments.\n251\t\n252\tFor each review comment:\n253\t\n254\t- If it is right, push a follow-up commit that addresses it.\n255\t- If you are unsure, ask a question on the PR.\n256\t- If you disagree, explain your reasoning briefly and respectfully.\n257\t\n258\tAfter pushing updates, leave a short comment saying what changed. GitHub does\n259\tnot always make it obvious which comments were addressed by a new commit.\n260\t\n261\t## If You Get Stuck\n262\t\n263\tAsk early, and include context. Good help requests include:\n264\t\n265\t- What you are trying to do.\n266\t- The command you ran.\n267\t- The exact error or output.\n268\t- What you already checked.\n269\t- Your OS and Go version when setup or tests are involved.\n270\t\n271\tUseful places to ask:\n272\t\n273\t- The GitHub issue you are working on.\n274\t- The pull request, if one is already open.\n275\t- [Discord](https://discord.gg/jZJs3Tue4S) for general questions.\n276\t\n277\t## Quick Checklist\n278\t\n279\tBefore opening your first PR:\n280\t\n281\t- You picked a small, focused change.\n282\t- You asked for maintainer scope before non-trivial code work.\n283\t- You created a branch from current `main`.\n284\t- You ran the checks that match your change.\n285\t- Your PR description explains what changed and how you tested it.\n286\t\n287\tThank you for taking the time to contribute. Small, careful improvements make\n288\tthe project easier for the next person too.\n289\t"}]},"uuid":"08153584-84f8-4946-b196-8fc0eb67368d","timestamp":"2026-05-12T16:47:41.793Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/goose-guest/Documents/work/cli/docs/first-time-contributors.md","content":"# First-Time Contributors\n\nWelcome. This guide is for people who are new to Entire, new to open source, or\njust want a careful path through their first contribution to this repository.\n\nThe main contribution rules live in [CONTRIBUTING.md](../CONTRIBUTING.md). Treat\nthat file as the source of truth. This page slows the process down and explains\nwhere to start, what to say, what to run, and what to expect after you open a\npull request.\n\n## Who This Is For\n\nStart here if any of these are true:\n\n- You have never opened a pull request before.\n- You have contributed to other projects, but not to Entire.\n- You want help finding a contribution that is small enough to finish.\n- You are unsure how to ask maintainers for the right amount of context.\n\nIf you are already comfortable with this repo, use the shorter workflow in\n[CONTRIBUTING.md](../CONTRIBUTING.md).\n\n## Choose a First Contribution\n\nStart by browsing [GitHub Issues](https://github.com/entireio/cli/issues) for\nissues that describe behavior you can reproduce, mention a command or workflow\nyou can try locally, or feel concrete enough that you can explain the problem\nback in your own words. You can also check the `#looking-for-contributors`\nchannel in Discord. You do not need to understand the whole project before\nasking about an issue.\n\nGood first contributions are small, clear, and easy to review. For this repo,\nthat usually means one of these:\n\n- Reproducing a bug you personally hit and adding the missing test.\n- Clarifying a confusing CLI message, help text, or setup step.\n- Adding a focused test around existing command behavior.\n- Fixing a small platform-specific issue on macOS, Linux, or Windows.\n- Improving README or contributor instructions after you hit real friction.\n\nWhen looking at an issue, favor ones where you can explain the problem back in\nyour own words. It is okay if you do not know the fix yet. If an issue is broad,\ncomment with the part you think you can tackle and ask whether that slice would\nbe useful.\n\nIf you do not already have a specific problem in mind, ask in\n`#looking-for-contributors` and mention what you are comfortable with, such as\nGo tests, CLI output, setup issues, Windows behavior, or README/contributor\nwording. A maintainer can usually point you toward a safer slice than browsing\nalone can.\n\nAs a first PR, avoid broad architecture changes, new agent integrations, command\nrenames, checkpoint strategy changes, or anything that changes git history\nbehavior unless a maintainer has already helped define the scope.\n\n## Comment Before You Start\n\nBefore starting non-trivial code work, leave a short comment on the issue or\nstart a new issue. This helps avoid duplicated effort and gives maintainers a\nchance to redirect you before you spend time on the wrong approach.\n\nA good first comment is specific:\n\n```text\nHi, I am new to Entire and would like to work on this.\n\nI was able to reproduce the issue by running:\n\n  entire status\n\nMy plan is to update the error message in <file or command area> and add a\nfocused test for the behavior. Does that sound like the right direction?\n```\n\nIf you are not starting from an existing issue, open one with the smallest\nconcrete problem you can describe:\n\n```text\nI hit confusing behavior while running `entire enable` on macOS.\n\nExpected: the command would explain which agent config was missing.\nActual: the command exited with \"not configured\".\n\nI can reproduce this locally. Would a small PR that improves the message and\nadds a focused test be useful?\n```\n\nYou do not need a perfect plan. Showing what you have tried and where you are\nheaded is usually enough.\n\n## Set Up the Repository\n\nFork the repository on GitHub, then clone your fork:\n\n```bash\ngit clone git@github.com:YOUR-USERNAME/cli.git\ncd cli\n```\n\nAdd the upstream repository so you can pull in maintainer changes later:\n\n```bash\ngit remote add upstream git@github.com:entireio/cli.git\ngit fetch upstream\n```\n\nInstall the local toolchain:\n\n```bash\nmise trust\nmise install\ngo mod download\nmise run build\n```\n\nVerify the setup with the normal test suite:\n\n```bash\nmise run test\n```\n\nIf setup fails, include the command you ran, the full error text, your OS, and\nthe output of `go version` when asking for help.\n\n## Create a Branch\n\nCreate a branch from the latest `main`:\n\n```bash\ngit switch main\ngit pull upstream main\ngit switch -c fix/clearer-enable-error\n```\n\nUse a branch name that describes the change. Examples:\n\n- `fix/clearer-enable-error`\n- `test/session-status-output`\n- `docs/setup-troubleshooting-note`\n\n## Make a Small Change\n\nKeep your first pull request narrow. A focused PR is easier to review and easier\nto finish.\n\nGood first PR shapes:\n\n- One failing behavior plus its test.\n- One small error message improvement.\n- One test-only clarification.\n- One README or setup clarification based on a real problem you hit.\n\nAvoid bundling unrelated cleanup with your first PR. If you notice extra things\nwhile working, leave yourself a note and open a follow-up issue or PR later.\n\n## Use AI Carefully\n\nEntire CLI is not an agent. It is a CLI for capturing and navigating AI-agent\nwork, so it is completely normal to use coding agents while contributing.\nThere is no need to tell us that you used AI in your work.\n\nUse whatever agent and workflow you like. We hope you like Goose, of course. The\nimportant rule is that you are responsible for the final code, tests, and docs.\nBefore submitting a PR, review the diff yourself. PRs that look generated,\nunreviewed, or \"vibe coded\" without a human pass may be closed.\n\nQuick responsible AI tips:\n\n- **Think first.** Agents tend to jump straight to code. Ask the agent to explore\n  the codebase first, explain the relevant architecture, and propose an approach\n  before it edits files.\n- **Push back on shortcuts.** Watch for trivial tests, overly wide types,\n  optional fields added just to satisfy the compiler, swallowed errors, and\n  copied local patterns that do not actually fit.\n- **Notice uncertainty.** If the agent keeps declaring that it understands the\n  issue but the patches are not converging, stop and reframe the task. Use what\n  you learned to start a smaller attempt.\n- **Cut the bloat.** Remove redundant comments, just-in-case logging,\n  over-defensive branches, and tests that only check implementation details\n  instead of user-visible behavior.\n\n## Run the Right Checks\n\nFor wording-only changes, run a lightweight sanity check:\n\n```bash\ngit diff --check\n```\n\nFor Go code changes, run:\n\n```bash\nmise run fmt\nmise run lint\nmise run test\n```\n\nBefore a larger PR or when a maintainer asks for full verification, run:\n\n```bash\nmise run check\n```\n\nDo not run real agent E2E tests unless a maintainer explicitly asks you to. They\ncan make real agent API calls. The deterministic canary E2E suite is safe to run\nwhen your change touches E2E prompt wording or test infrastructure:\n\n```bash\nmise run test:e2e:canary\n```\n\n## Commit Your Work\n\nCommit with a short, descriptive message:\n\n```bash\ngit add <files you changed>\ngit commit -m \"Clarify enable error when agent config is missing\"\n```\n\nEntire is used to dogfood Entire. If you have the Entire CLI installed and\nenabled in this repository, the git hook may add an `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer\nto your commit message automatically. That is expected. See\n[Using Entire While Contributing](../CONTRIBUTING.md#using-entire-while-contributing)\nfor the full details.\n\n## Open a Pull Request\n\nPush your branch to your fork:\n\n```bash\ngit push -u origin fix/clearer-enable-error\n```\n\nThen open a pull request against `entireio/cli` on GitHub.\n\nIn the PR description, include:\n\n- The issue it addresses, if there is one.\n- A short summary of what changed.\n- The checks you ran, such as `mise run test` or `git diff --check`.\n- Anything you want reviewers to pay special attention to.\n\nIf your PR is not ready for final review yet, open it as a draft. Draft PRs are\nuseful when you want early feedback on direction.\n\n## Respond to Review\n\nReview is part of the contribution, not a sign that you did something wrong.\nEntire PRs may receive automated Copilot comments and maintainer comments.\n\nFor each review comment:\n\n- If it is right, push a follow-up commit that addresses it.\n- If you are unsure, ask a question on the PR.\n- If you disagree, explain your reasoning briefly and respectfully.\n\nAfter pushing updates, leave a short comment saying what changed. GitHub does\nnot always make it obvious which comments were addressed by a new commit.\n\n## If You Get Stuck\n\nAsk early, and include context. Good help requests include:\n\n- What you are trying to do.\n- The command you ran.\n- The exact error or output.\n- What you already checked.\n- Your OS and Go version when setup or tests are involved.\n\nUseful places to ask:\n\n- The GitHub issue you are working on.\n- The pull request, if one is already open.\n- [Discord](https://discord.gg/jZJs3Tue4S) for general questions.\n\n## Quick Checklist\n\nBefore opening your first PR:\n\n- You picked a small, focused change.\n- You asked for maintainer scope before non-trivial code work.\n- You created a branch from current `main`.\n- You ran the checks that match your change.\n- Your PR description explains what changed and how you tested it.\n\nThank you for taking the time to contribute. Small, careful improvements make\nthe project easier for the next person too.\n","numLines":289,"startLine":1,"totalLines":289}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"8b9db839-bae8-47d5-801f-4fd5bd0427f7","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-desktop","cwd":"/Users/goose-guest/Documents/work/skills/.claude/worktrees/strange-driscoll-873c0f","sessionId":"dfa3fdbd-f0ec-461d-b6c3-d40c4b05556b","version":"2.1.128","gitBranch":"claude/strange-driscoll-873c0f"}
